    // 1. i_0 < i_1 < ... < i_{k-1} (subsequence property)
    // 2. nums[i_j] = j (fixed point condition in the new array)

    // Let's rephrase the condition. If we select an element at original index i
    // to be at position j in the resulting array, we must have nums[i] = j.
    // Since the positions j are 0, 1, 2, ..., k-1, this means we are looking for
    // a subsequence where the value of the element equals its *new* index.

    // Let dp[j] be the minimum original index 'i' such that nums[i] = j, and 'i' is part
    // of a valid sequence of length j+1 (i.e., the element at position j). This seems complicated.

    // Let's use a simpler greedy approach based on the observation:
    // If we select elements to form the longest possible fixed point sequence,
    // say of length K, the elements must satisfy:
    // Selected elements: nums[i_0], nums[i_1], ..., nums[i_{K-1}]
    // Required values: 0, 1, ..., K-1
    // Required indices: i_0 < i_1 < ... < i_{K-1}
    // And the condition: nums[i_j] = j.

    // We want to find the longest sequence of indices i_0 < i_1 < ... < i_{K-1}
    // such that nums[i_j] = j for all j in [0, K-1].

    // This is a direct greedy matching problem. We try to match the required value j
    // (which is the new index) with an element nums[i] such that nums[i] = j,
    // and we pick the one with the smallest possible original index i that is
    // greater than the previously picked index.

    let current_required_value = 0; // This is the required new index (j)
    let last_original_index = -1;  // Index of the last element chosen (i_{j-1})
    let fixed_points_count = 0;

    // Iterate through all elements of the original array nums
    for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
        // Check if the current element nums[i] can satisfy the requirement for the
        // next available position (current_required_value).
        // Condition: nums[i] must equal current_required_value.
        if (nums[i] === current_required_value) {
            // We found a match! This element can be the next fixed point.
            // Since we iterate i in increasing order, this element is guaranteed
